<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 94 / Aeroflot airlines to be sold off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Russia's Aeroflot, once the world's biggest airline monopoly but split into
321 small airlines since the Soviet collapse, plans to sell a 49 per cent
stake at a privatisation auction, officials said, Reuter reports from
Moscow. The former flag carrier would sell its shares for cash at an
investment tender soon but no final date has been set, Aeroflot officials
said yesterday.
The government would keep a majority 51 per cent stake in the Russian
state's international carrier, which became a joint stock company this week
to allow privatisation after two years of chaotic reorganisation. Aeroflot's
privatisation was delayed by a dispute between airline officials and the
government over whether it should be split up or sold as a single lot. But
airline officials said Aeroflot's 'daughter' companies would also be
privatised. The proceeds of the sell-off would go towards purchases of new
equipment and spare parts.
They gave no details about the sell-off, but privatisation officials say
public offerings for cash - due to start from July 1 after the expiry of the
voucher privatisation - will involve sales of block shares to foreign and
domestic investors. Russia's Aeroflot to sell 49 per cent of stakes.
Hundreds of domestic and international airlines have been set up since
Aeroflot was broken up as part of post-communist market reforms, plunging
civil aviation into chaos.
