<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 94 / Finance and the Family: Directors' transactions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIVIEN MACDONALD, The Inside Track
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Every year as summer begins, the number of deals by directors tails off.
Thus, it is unusual to note a steady number buying at present.
Seven members of the board at Life Sciences International, a maker of
scientific and hospital equipment, took the opportunity offered by a dip in
the share price to buy stock at 117p. The largest single purchase was by Sir
Christopher Bland, previously the chairman of London Weekend Television, who
bought 1m to more than double his holding.
Halkin Holdings used to be known as Hoskins Breweries. Over the past year it
has had a complete change of management, and its share price has begun to
perform better. Directors bought last summer at 55p and have been back in
the market again. Chairman Howard Hodgson and Bruce McGuire acquired 50,000
each at around 62p.
Dewhirst Group, a clothing and toiletries company, featured in this column
when vice-chairman James Dewhirst bought stock in May. The share price has
moved very little since then and another two directors have taken the
opportunity to get into the market. Chairman Timothy Dewhirst and Robin
Horsell, an executive director, bought 120,000 and 19,960 respectively at
123p. Timothy Dewhirst now holds more than 4.9m while Horsell's holding is
more than 850,000.
Quicks Group, a motor distributor, has enjoyed steady price increases over
the past two years. In the summer of 1992 Alexander Murray, the chief
executive, and managing director, and Frederick Royle bought stock around
110p. Timothy Franey, a non-executive director, has taken the opportunity to
sell some stock - initially at 185p last September and latterly at 190p. He
remains the single largest shareholder on the board with 4.6 per cent of the
stock.
