<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Gains reversed after gilts prompt
late sell-off - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK stock market, encouraged at first by a better tone in global bond
markets, turned off in late dealings yesterday when gilt-edged securities
fell on the announcement that next week's auction of government securities
will be a further tranche of Floating Rate Treasury stock.
The last day of the UK equity trading account was dominated by expiry
operations in derivatives markets in London, Frankfurt and New York. Traders
ascribed an initial gain of nearly 20 points on the Footsie Index to the
traditional book-squaring operations surrounding the expiry, at about
10.20am, of index options and index futures on the London International
Financial Futures (LIFFE) market.
The day's peak of 3,049.7 left intact the upper end of the current trading
range. Shares drifted lower once the derivatives expiry was out of the way
and the Footsie showed a fall of 13.1 at 3,017 as London waited to see if
New York would build on its overnight gain.
The FT-SE Index closed a net 7.2 down at 3,022.9, with the Dow Average 8
points off as London traders set off for home. British Petroleum stocks
continued to do well on the back of more positive views on oil prices, and
both Enterprise Oil and Lasmo, its bid target, strengthened as the market
awaited developments.
The broader market, less closely linked to the derivatives expiries, traded
easier and the FT-SE Mid 250 Index fell 7.1 to 3,527.1. Seaq business
increased to 736.8m shares from 619.8m on Thursday, with non-Footsie stocks
making up around 62 per cent of the total - a further indication of the
focus on the derivatives-linked blue chips.
The Footsie has fallen by 33 points over a week which has seen investment
confidence challenged by domestic and international factors. The Mansion
House speeches from the UK chancellor of the exchequer and the governor of
the Bank of England failed to unsettle equities in spite of their rejection
of early tax cut suggestions and warning that UK base rates will rise later
this year.
But renewed uncertainty in world bond markets such as oil and commodity
prices has arisen, because at one stage this week international doubts
unsettled shares and continued to overhang markets last night.
Over the two-week account which closed last night, the Footsie has risen by
about 0.8 per cent, leaving the 3,000 mark still a testing level for market
support. UK equities have found it impossible to move far away from this
level over the past month.
Government bonds put on more than half a point in early trading yesterday
before turning off smartly on the news of a Floating Rate auction, which was
seen as an indication that the authorities are as aware as the market of the
uncertain mood of the bond market. By the close, long-dated gilts were a net
 5/32 lower, with the shorts just a touch off on the day.
The gilt-edged team at Yamaichi commented to clients that the bond market is
'caught in the dual grip' of domestic uncertainty on inflation policy and
the global inflation concerns reflected across the broader range of bond
markets. Yamaichi believes that the UK market has established a wide trading
range consistent with these uncertainties. While confident that gilts will
break out higher as investors perceive that inflation concerns have been
overdone, Yamaichi sees a downside risk in the near term.
</TEXT>
<XX>
