FT  18 JUN 94 / International Company News: Ex-FT chief joins O'Reilly group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Palmer, the former chief executive of the Financial Times Group, is
to be managing director of Independent Newspapers (Ireland), the Irish
publishing division of Mr Tony O'Reilly's expanding media group.
As well as being responsible for the Dublin-based group's main Irish titles
 -the Irish Independent, Evening Herald and Sunday Independent - Mr Palmer
will join the main board.
Mr Palmer, 53, spent 29 years with the FT as reporter, news editor and
deputy editor before moving into newspaper management. When he left the FT
abruptly in April 1993, Pearson, the paper's owners, cited 'differences in
management style'.
Mr O'Reilly, chairman of HJ Heinz as well as chairman of Independent
Newspapers, has been talking to Mr Palmer for several months following the
departure of the previous managing director, Mr Joe Hayes, in March to
pursue other business interests.
Mr Palmer, educated at Eton and Oxford, will move to Dublin to take up his
new appointment.
In the mid 1980s the former FT chief executive was in charge of a Pounds 75m
investment plan to introduce photo-composition at the paper and build its
new Docklands printing plant.
Although Independent Newspapers has expanded into South Africa, France,
Mexico, the UK and Australia, the core is still its main Irish newspapers.
Last year pre-tax profits rose 81 per cent to IPounds 29m (Pounds 28.4m).
</TEXT>
