<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUN 94 / Prince of Wales to pay Pounds 1m tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Prince of Wales is expected to pay about Pounds 1m in his first tax bill
since he volunteered last year to pay income tax.
The prince will pay 40 per cent of the revenues of the Duchy of Cornwall,
which totalled Pounds 4.08m in 1993, after deducting the costs of his
official duties. The details of his tax returns have not been finalised, but
the total is expected to be similar to the sum under the former system when
he voluntarily surrendered 25 per cent of the duchy's total income.
The duchy's accounts, published yesterday, showed that net income for the
year had increased from Pounds 3.41m to Pounds 4.08m. The value of the
duchy's assets increased from Pounds 76.2m to Pounds 87.7m. Income from
farmland and property was Pounds 9.1m compared with operating costs of
Pounds 5.6m. The high operating costs stemmed from the wide geographical
spread of holdings and higher-than-average maintenance standards. A further
Pounds 1.05m of income came from stockmarket investments, offset by a Pounds
1.05m interest charge that stemmed from acquisitions of commercial property
in the late 1980s.
The Duchy of Cornwall was created in 1337 by Edward III for the Black Prince
to provide an income for the heir to the throne. It comprises 130,000 acres
of agricultural land, mainly in the south-west of England and the Isles of
Scilly, a residential and property portfolio, and a Pounds 40m quoted
investment portfolio in environmentally sound companies.
The duchy said it aimed to be efficient, forward-looking and commercially
sensible while seeking to respond to the interests and concerns of the
prince.
The prince's advisers are finalising his tax return with the Inland Revenue.
All expenses connected with official duties, including the running of his
62-strong office, entertainment and uniforms, are allowable against tax.
</TEXT>
