FT  18 JUN 94 / Canadian inflation below zero
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Inflation in Canada has disappeared, with the year-on-year consumer price
index falling in May for the first time since mid-1955. Statistics Canada
said yesterday that consumer prices fell by 0.2 per cent last month. The
annual inflation rate for the year to May was also minus 0.2 per cent.
Inflation has been falling steadily since 1991 when it reached a peak of 5.9
per cent. High interest rates and the 1991-93 recession gave the initial
impetus to weakening prices.
