FT  18 JUN 94 / US telephone company ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEREMY KAHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Federal regulators in the US cannot apply more lenient regulatory
requirements to smaller long-distance telephone companies, the Supreme Court
ruled yesterday. The Federal Communications Commission had allowed smaller
long-distance carriers, including MCI Communications and Sprint, to offer
rates and services without having to specify them to the FCC.
Because of the high cost of filing with the FCC, agency officials believed
that relaxing regulations on smaller telephone companies would allow them to
better compete against American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, which controls 60 per
cent of the long-distance market.
