<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (34): Those barefoot
millionaires - Third World
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMANUEL MARADAS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Third World of soccer is not the same as the economic Third World.
Football's backward nations include prosperous Japan, while impoverished
Latin America joins wealthy Europe among the game's aristocrats, writes
Emmanuel Maradas
Nowhere will the unfolding drama in the US be followed more closely than in
football's Third World, where whole countries will grind to a halt to follow
the national team's fortunes in Dallas, San Francisco or New York.
In reality, there are two football Third Worlds. The first is the economic
Third World, embracing the city slums of Latin America, Africa and the Far
East. The symbolic power of possibly the world's greatest ever footballer,
Brazil's Pele, resides not so much in his skills on the pitch, however
startling, as in his rise from favela to international stage.
In nations such as Cameroon, football excellence is a chance to forget the
misery of everyday existence and assert a presence on the world stage. Look
at us,' such countries say. We can barely afford to eat, but in one area at
least, we are better than the richest of you.'
Hence too, the palpable sense of brotherhood across national boundaries. All
Africa supported Cameroon during the 1990 World Cup in Italy; if the African
sides are knocked out, their loyalty will always go to Brazil, Colombia or
Argentina, rather than Germany or Italy.
For individual players, who for the most part learned their football
barefoot in the empty lots of Third World cities, soccer offers one of the
few escape routes - barring a life of crime - from a life of drudgery. The
golden window opens for only a very few, but those who squeeze through it to
a life as professional players in Europe or elsewhere return home as heroes,
educate their children and live in a style unattainable by any other means.
So much for the economic Third World. On the pitch, economics are tipped
partly on their heads. Here, Latin America stands alongside Europe among the
elite, while the Third World embraces the rising football continents of
Africa and Asia. In this topsy-turvy world, economic superstars Japan and
South Korea, where football is still finding its feet, in many ways have
more in common with Morocco, Cameroon or Nigeria than with the rich nations
of the West.
In world football politics, Asia and Africa almost invariably vote as a
bloc, struggling to make their voices heard against the European and Latin
American barons. Africa fought long and hard to win its third place in the
World Cup finals; Asia is still trying to catch up. Europe dominates, with
13 of the 24 teams in contention in the US, and retains its stranglehold
over decisions shaping the future of the world game.
Will the Africans and Asians make an impact in the US? This will be the the
first World Cup in which Africa has had three representatives, thanks mainly
to Cameroon's brilliant showing in Italy four years ago. Asia keeps its two
places, filled by newcomers Saudi Arabia and third-time qualifiers South
Korea. In Africa, standards have improved massively since Morocco became the
continent's first regular participant in the finals in 1970, and Zaire were
humiliated 9-0 by Yugoslavia four years later. The continent already sets
the standard at junior and youth levels: together, Nigeria and Ghana have
won three out of the five Under-17 world championships held under Fifa
auspices and come second twice; the same two countries respectively took
silver at Under-20 level in 1989 and 1993.
Many of the youngsters given international exposure at this level have gone
on to successful careers in the European professional game, gaining a depth
of experience which means they can face the best of Europe and Latin America
on equal terms.
Locally-based players continue to lag behind. In few African countries do
they receive a regular salary; many national stadiums would be a disgrace to
an English third division club, and physiotherapy and training facilities
are almost non-existent. All three African squads for the US are thus built
around a core of overseas-based professionals.
In Asia, the equation is reversed. Local championships in countries such as
Japan and Saudi Arabia are awash with money and the facilities are as good
as anywhere in the world. As a result, there is little incentive for Asian
professionals to look abroad. Add the fact that Asian players are generally
not as robust or as skilful as the Africans, and it is not surprising that
the world's most populous continent has so far made such a feeble impact on
global football.
All that could yet change as China, the sleeping giant of world soccer,
finally awakes under a plan launched last year to develop the sport from
school level upwards. In the meantime, however, Saudi Arabia and South Korea
seem cast in the role of also-rans in the US. The Saudis, in Group F, will
do well to snatch a single point against Belgium, Netherlands and Morocco.
Group C, meanwhile, sees the Koreans lined up against reigning champions
Germany, as well as strong sides from Spain and Bolivia.
The Africans, on the other hand, have high expectations of USA 1994. All
three have taken their preparations much more seriously than before, taking
part in a merry-go-round of friendlies across the globe. Nigeria's Super
Eagles, fresh from their victory in the African championships in Tunisia
this April, boast an attacking combination to put fear into any opponent.
Cameroon have appalling money troubles, and the administrators have probably
spent twice as much energy squabbling among themselves over the past year as
preparing for the tournament. But nobody will underestimate the Indomitable
Lions' potential to cause havoc, and they - like Morocco - have a good deal
of national pride at stake.
As to Latin America, might 1994 be Brazil's year? The green-and-golds have
never missed a World Cup finals, and after a decade in the wilderness they
might just be in shape to regain their place at the summit of the world
game. Argentina, Colombia, Mexico and Bolivia will also be there, banging at
the door.
Barring miracles from the African and Asian sides, the Third World will be
rooting for a Brazilian victory. The day that Romario, Rai, Jorginho and
colleagues hold up the World Cup trophy, it will be the proof that every
child, whatever the continent, can rise out of the dust and make his mark on
the world.
Emmanuel Maradas is editor of African Soccer magazine
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XMZ  Africa.
    XOZ  Asia.
    XCZ  Latin America.
</CN>
<XX>
