<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (33): Group F - Fixtures and
facts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Group Fixtures
Sunday, June 19 - Belgium v Morocco
12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
Orlando - Citrus Bowl
Monday, June 20 - Netherlands v Saudi Arabia - 19:30 local (23:30 GMT)
Washington - RFK Stadium
Saturday, June 25 - Saudi Arabia v Morocco
12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
New York - Giants stadium
Saturday, June 25 - Belgium v Netherlands - 12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
Orlando - Citrus Bowl
Wednesday, June 29 - Morocco v Netherlands - 12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
Orlando - Citrus Bowl
Wednesday, June 29 - Belgium v Saudi Arabia - 12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
Washington - RFK Stadium
Star Player: Vincenzo Scifo
Country: Belgium
Club: Monaco - (also: Anderlecht, Torino, Auxerre, Bordeaux)
Age: 28
Scifo the prodigy is now in his prime. He played in his first World Cup in
Mexico at 20. His club form has often been inconsistent but in the 1990
World Cup he was often masterful. In Bologna he gave Paul Gascoigne a
two-hour lesson in midfield play before Gazza's long punt forward created
Platt's miraculous late winner. He is an excellent passer of the ball but he
can also beat a player and shoot from long distance. His neat, unspectacular
style often serves to disguise his gifts but, in a World Cup rather short of
old fashioned playmakers, he will be well worth watching.
Key Game: Belgium v Netherlands (June 25 - Orlando)
This is high noon for the low countries. The Dutch are unhappy about having
to play twice at mid-day in central Florida in June. The Dutch know that the
heat will give Morocco their best hope of victory in the final group match.
Even so, and in spite of the heat and humidity, the match offers the two
teams the only true chance to test their pretensions against serious
opposition before the demanding matches of the later rounds. - A victory for
either team here will secure a place in the second round - assuming both
sides win comfortably against Saudi Arabia - and will also go some way to
appeasing fans at home regardless of what happens next: the shape of the
draw means both the winner and runner-up in this group will face difficult
second round matches.
</TEXT>
