<PROFILE>_AN-EFQDGAIGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (30): Group F - Morocco
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMANUEL MARADAS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is the third time Morocco have qualified for the finals, each time in
the Americas. In 1970, in Mexico, they were the first African side since
Egypt in 1934 to take part; 16 years later, again in Mexico, they became the
first to reach the second round.
In 1994 there is more than the usual dose of national pride at stake.
Morocco is still angry about the way its bids to host the World Cup, in 1994
and 1998, were brushed aside in favour of the US and France. King Hassan II
has put massive funds at the disposal of the team, and national coach
Abdallah Blinda will have some explaining to do if his charges do not reach
the second round.
He has decided to call mainly on overseas-based players, principally those
playing in Europe. The key to the side is undoubtedly Rashid Daoudi (WAC
Casablanca), a midfielder known as Magic Daoudi'. He is joined in midfield
by rising star Mustafa Hajji (23), who plays for Nancy in the French second
division.
Experience is represented by Mustafa al-Haddaoui (Angers), the sole survivor
of the 1986 World Cup squad. But many of the overseas contingent, having
grown up abroad, do not speak Arabic and have no language in common with
their home-based colleagues. If things begin to go wrong, the language
division could prove crucial.
The strategy will be to draw with either Belgium or the Netherlands and
notch up a good win over Saudi Arabia. That would see them through to the
second round. Success thereafter will be celebrated all the way to the royal
palace in Rabat.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>MAZ  Morocco, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P794  Commercial Sports.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XX
</PAGE>
