<DOCNO>FT942-2680</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EFQDGAIEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (28): Group E - Fixtures and
facts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Group Fixtures
Saturday, June 18 - Italy v Ireland - 16:00 local (20:00 GMT)
New York - Giants Stadium
Sunday, June 19 - Norway v Mexico - 16:00 local (20:00 GMT)
Washington - RFK Stadium
Thursday, June 23 - Italy v Norway
16:00 local (20:00 GMT)
New York - Giants Stadium
Friday, June 24 - Mexico v Ireland
12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
Orlando - Citrus Bowl
Tuesday, June 28 - Italy v Mexico
12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
Washington - RFK Stadium
Tuesday, June 28 - Ireland v Norway
12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
New York - Giants Stadium
Star Player: Giuseppe Signori
Country: Italy
Club: Lazio (also Leffe, Piacenza, Trento, Foggia)
Age: 26
Italy have a habit of leaning heavily on one man to supply World Cup goals.
Toto Schillaci scored five of their eight goals in 1990. Altobelli scored
four of Italy's five in Mexico in 1986. In 1982, Paolo Rossi, silent as
Italy trudged through the group matches, hit six goals in the last three
games to carry Italy to victory. Signori is quick, brave, bright and
skilful, but his greatest asset is his ferocious shot. He has no backlift,
so goalkeepers and defenders have little time to react; yet he shoots with
power and accuracy. He blasts penalties while standing still. He can score
against any defence. If he does so Italy will go far.
Key Game: Italy v Ireland (June 20 - San Francisco)
This is the hottest ticket in the World Cup. This match has captured the
imagination of New York, and not just its strident Irish and Italian
communities. The atmosphere should be raucous even if many spectators do not
really understand the game which will provide an intriguing contrast of
styles. It will also be fiercely contested. Neither team dares lose and both
will want the three points and the likely place in the last 16 a win brings.
Last time the two countries met Ireland had completed their fairy-tale run
to the quarter-finals in 1990 and were happy to die valiantly, exhausted at
the host's feet. Now, World Cup veterans and fresh from friendly wins
against the Netherlands and Germany, they, and their opponents, will have a
higher opinion of what the green shirts can achieve.
</TEXT>
<XX>
