<PROFILE>_AN-EFQDGAIDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (27): Group E - Ireland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In 1990, Ireland rolled up for their first World Cup with the oldest squad
in the competition, failed to win a game and still found themselves in a
quarter-final against Italy in Rome. The strengths and weaknesses that
characterised that campaign will still be the hallmarks of the Irish team
this time.
They work hard, stick to manager Jack Charlton's simple plan and have much
better players than many critics realise - except in attack. They will again
struggle to score goals. In Italy they drew all three group games before
beating Romania on penalties after a goal-less draw and then restricting the
hosts to a 1-0 win.
This time they are in the toughest group. The change to three points for a
win in group games will penalise Ireland, who have lost the best of their
lacklustre crew of goalscorers, Niall Quinn (Manchester City), to injury.
Charlton's squad includes just four attackers. But it has had a much needed
infusion of youth: Roy Keane (Manchester United), a midfield bull, Garry
Kelly (Leeds United) a pacey defender and Jason McAteer (Bolton Wanderers),
a promising Liverpudlian midfielder who has opted for Ireland. They are
potentially top class and perfectly suit Charlton's system. - If some of
Charlton's ageing stars, notably Paul McGrath, Andy Townsend and Ray
Houghton (all Aston Villa), can shake off the lethargy that has settled over
their club play, Ireland will again be difficult to beat.
Recent friendlies, capped by a 2-0 win in Germany, have gone well. Tony
Cascarino, an ungainly centre forward not good enough to command a starting
place in Chelsea's routed FA Cup Final team, has brought aerial power to
Ireland's direct attacks.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IEZ  Ireland, EC.
</CN>
