<PROFILE>_AN-EFQDGAIAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (24): Group E - Italy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's manager, Arrigo Sacchi, is spoilt for choice. And if he carries on
as he did in the qualifying tournament the very richness of his squad may
prove Italy's undoing.
In his first two-and-a-half years in charge Sacchi picked more than 70
players. Entering the World Cup it is still not clear what he thinks his
best team is. Will he play Roberto Baggio in midfield or in attack? Even
though Robberto Mancini (Sampdoria) has dropped out, Sacchi still has
attacking decisions to make. Will he pick goalscorer Giuseppe Signori
(Lazio) - small, quick, skilful, ferocious shot - or Daniele Massaro (Milan)
 -small, quick, skilful, ferocious shot - or both? Or will he opt for the
height of goal-shy Pierluigi Casiraghi (Lazio) or the creative talents of
Gianfranco Zola (Parma)? The permutations are endless and Sacchi seems to
have been trying to run through them all. - Sacchi revolutionised Italian
football when he managed AC Milan. His team combined traditional Italian
skills with an up-tempo, pressing approach. Under his coaching the team won
the Italian league and two European Cups. Now he wants the national team to
play his system. There is little doubt that this works. But, as he says, if
he can persuade 22 players to fit into one system it will be an Italian
record'.
Sacchi is astute enough to know that if Italy are to fulfil their potential
and challenge for the World Cup he will need to find a settled team with
settled nerves.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
