<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (23): Group D - Fixtures and
facts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Group Fixtures
Tuesday, June 21 - Argentina v Greece - 12:30 local (16:30 GMT)
Boston - Foxboro Stadium
Tuesday, June 21 - Nigeria v Bulgaria - 18:30 local (23:30 GMT)
Dallas - Cotton Bowl
Saturday, June 25 - Argentina v Nigeria - 16:00 local (20:00 GMT)
Boston - Foxboro Stadium
Sunday, June 26 - Bulgaria v Greece - 11:30 local (16:30 GMT)
Chicago - Soldier Fields Stadium
Thursday, June 30 - Greece v Nigeria - 19:30 local (23:30 GMT)
Boston - Foxboro Stadium
Thursday, June 30 - Argentina v Bulgaria - 18:30 local (23:30 GMT)
Dallas - Cotton Bowl
Star Player: Augustine Jay-Jay Okocha
Country: Nigeria
Club: Eintracht Frankfurt
Age: 20
Position: Midfield or attack
Okocha is the most promising of Nigeria's rich crop of young stars, who won
the World Under-17 Cup in 1985, were runners up in 1987 and finished second
in the World U-20 cup in 1989. Big, strong Rashidi Yekini, a 30-year old
centre forward, will be the focus of attention for opposing defences, but he
cannot carry Nigeria far on his own. The form of the young Eagles, has
helped Nigeria to win the African Nations Cup and to reach their first World
Cup finals. Okocha can score from midfield and is a threat from free kicks.
He holds the key to Nigeria's progress in the US and beyond. -
Key Game: Argentina v Nigeria (June 25 - Boston)
Argentina have a chance to exorcise the ghost of their opening defeat to
Cameroon in Italy four years ago when they meet the most-fancied of the
African nations in this World Cup. Nigeria are appearing in their first
World Cup but their ambition is to go further than Cameroon did in 1990.
They do not lack experience, their team is packed with men who play in
European football. They are big, strong, fast, skilful and every bit as
rough as Cameroon. Argentina have a better attack than they did in 1990 but
their greatest strength is still their uncompromising defence. This will be
a severe test of both teams' pretensions and of Fifa's directive to referees
to punish overly physical play and tackles from behind.
Penalty king: Sergio Goicochea of Argentina
Stupendous power: Rashidi Yekini of Nigeria
</TEXT>
