<PROFILE>_AN-EFQDGAH7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (21): Group D - Bulgaria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY OLIVER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
France against Bulgaria, November 17, 1993. One minute left, 1-1, and France
have as good as qualified for the World Cup. Bulgaria break away with Penev.
He passes to Kostadinov who shoots. - He scores and Bulgaria and not France
have qualified. The French look dazed. Needing just one point from their
last two games, they have lost both in the last minute. - Bulgaria has a
poor World Cup record. In 16 attempts during the finals they have yet to win
a game, but Kostadinov's goal, unexpected and brilliant as it was, will give
them the impetus to break that duck. They will fancy their chances of
reaching the second round, mainly because of their formidable striking
options.
Bulgaria will resemble an Iberian select XI. With the exception of the
goalkeeper who plays in France, all of the team's foreign-based players play
their club football in Spain or Portugal. Their three first choice forwards
are Ivailo Yordanov of Sporting Lisbon, Emil Kostadinov of Porto and
Barcelona's Hristo Stoichkov. Stoichkov is capable of winning a match almost
on his own and will be one of the most marked men in America.
The midfield is held together by Krasimir Balakov (Sporting Lisbon) and
Zlatko Yankov, but the main area of worry for coach Dimitar Penev is the
defence. Unlike previous Bulgarian teams, the present side plays open
attractive football which leaves them vulnerable at the back.
Gone are the days when the Bulgarians would grind out results in true
communist fashion. In Mexico eight years ago they qualified for the second
round with three turgid displays. They have yet to convince the public that
they have turned over a new leaf. Ticket sales in Dallas, where Bulgaria
play their first two games, are the lowest of all venues.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BGZ  Bulgaria, East Europe.
</CN>
