<PROFILE>_AN-EFQDGAH6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (20): Group D - Nigeria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   Be EMMANUEL MARADAS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nigeria's Super Eagles are first-time qualifiers for the finals, but they go
to the US ranked seventh in the world and fresh from victory in the African
Cup of Nations in April.
At last, it seems, technical adviser Clemens Westerhof has welded a
match-winning combination out of the dispersed talents that make up Nigerian
football.
Success has been a long time coming for Africa's most populous nation, which
has so often failed to live up to its potential.
The Super Eagles squad is made up mainly of overseas-based professionals.
The outstanding talent is probably Rashidi Yekini. A striker of stupendous
power, who plays for Vitoria Setubal in Portugal, Yekini is the African
Footballer of the Year and was top scorer in both the 1992 and 1994 Nations
Cups. At 31, he is nearing the end of his career but he could be one of the
tournament's most exciting talents. - The Eagles' midfield, featuring Sunday
Oliseh, Austin Okocha and Mutiu Adepoju, is the rival of any in the world.
Their most suspect department is the defence. Benedict Iroha, a goal scoring
defender, is a definite for the side. But the rest of the back line are
untested against a world class attack.
Nigeria's most difficult fixture will be against Argentina, who were
ambushed by Cameroon in the opening game of the 1990 World Cup. Bulgaria and
Greece are unlikely to offer much obstacle on the way to the second round.
Nigeria's ambitions are much higher. - Football is almost a religion in
Nigeria, and the authorities know that success in the US could help keep the
lid on a disastrous economic situation. If harmony continues to reign in the
Nigerian camp, the Super Eagles could coalesce into a squad to astonish the
world.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NGZ  Nigeria, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P794  Commercial Sports.
</IN>
<XX>
