<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (14): Group C - Spain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Spain are football's great under-achievers. Their club sides continue to
match the Germans and Italians for success in the European cups but the
national team does not. Their best World Cup finish was fourth in 1950. They
have qualified for the last three World Cups, but the pattern is always the
same. They come through the first round fairly comfortably but then go
quietly.
The problem is no doubt partly psychological and this team does not seem to
possess the talent to break that cycle. World class players such as Emilio
Butrage 1/16 o, Michel and Martin Vazquez have gone and been replaced by
lesser players. Only Julen Guerrero (Athletic Bilbao), just 20, offers
flair. The rest of the team is made up of disciplined, industrious, hardened
professionals. The frequently outrageous coach Javier Clemente is likely to
provide more entertainment than his team. The make-up of the group should
allow Spain to reach the next round as usual, but they are unlikely to
progress further.
</TEXT>
