<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (12): Group B - Fixtures and
facts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Group Fixtures
Sunday, June 19 - Cameroon v Sweden - 16:30 local (23:30 GMT)
Los Angeles - Rose Bowl
Monday, June 20
Brazil v Russia - 13:00 local (20:00 GMT)
San Francisco - Stanford Stadium
Friday, June 24 - Brazil v Cameroon - 13:00 local (20:00 GMT)
San Francisco - Stanford Stadium
Friday, June 24 - Sweden v Russia - 19:30 local (23:30 GMT)
Detroit - Pontiac Silverdome
Tuesday, June 28 - Brazil v Sweden - 16:00 (20:00 GMT)
Detroit - Pontiac Silverdome
Tuesday, June 28 - Russia v Cameroon - 13:00 local (20:00 GMT)
San Francisco - Stanford Stadium
Star Player: Rai
Country: Brazil
Club: Paris St Germain (Sao Paolo)
Age: 28
Brazil are spoilt for strikers but will depend heavily on Rai for midfield
creativity. Rai is the younger brother of Socrates, the leggy bearded
midfielder who played for Brazil in 1982 and 1986. Rai scored both goals for
Sao Paolo when they won the world club championship in 1992. This season he
moved to Europe and has allegedly played lethargically for his new club,
Paris St Germain. Nevertheless, PSG romped to their first French title, so
Rai cannot have been a passenger the whole time. Sao Paolo provided a
reminder of the greatest Brazilian football. Rai - must do for Brazil what
he did for his club.
Key Game: Brazil v Russia (June 20 - San Francisco)
The two most talented teams in the World Cup have warmed up with bitter
arguments over money. The Brazilians are used to this, but the Russian
players were brought up in the old Soviet sports system and are just
learning that the correct way to deal with incompetent, bullying football
administrators is to act like spoilt children. Both teams have long records
of World Cup frustrations. Russia's traditional World Cup is a mix of great
football - a 6-0 win over Hungary in 1986, 4-0 over Cameroon in 1990 - and
daft eliminations. They rarely fail to entertain and have played well in
warm up matches. They are the perfect opponents to bring out the best in
Brazil. And as go Brazil so goes the World Cup. A good early win could
encourage the masters to dazzle.
Strike breaker: Sergei Yuran, the Benfica attacker, will play for Russia
</TEXT>
