<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (11): Group B - Sweden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sweden are the overachievers of World Cup football. This is their ninth
appearance in the finals. They were fourth in 1938, third in 1950, runners
up as hosts in 1958. But after 1974 (quarter-finals) their record tails off.
They missed 1982 and 1986 and suffered a nasty first-round prang in Italy -
losing to Brazil, Scotland and, worst of all, Costa Rica.
Sweden are in a tough group but the team is equipped to make solid progress.
They have an experienced goalkeeper, Thomas Ravelli (Gothenburg), a
hard-working midfield anchored by Jonas Thern (Naples) and Stefan Schwarz
(Arsenal) and a strong centre-forward, Martin Dahlin (Borussia
Moenchengladbach).
All the players offer the typical mix of characteristics found in
professionals across western continental Europe: easy ball skills, physical
fitness, stamina and a willingness to submerge themselves in a team plan.
However, perhaps for those reasons, the team is short of flair and relies
overheavily on the subtle talents of chubby Thomas Brolin (Parma) who
emerged from the wreckage of the 1990 competition as a 20-year-old star. The
more unpredictable Anders Limpar (Everton) may add some spice to their play,
but the Swedes will bring an earnestness to their attempts to emulate past
performances.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>SEZ  Sweden, West Europe.
</CN>
