<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (10): Group B - Cameroon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMANUEL MARADAS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Everyone remembers the Indomitable Lions in 1990. Cameroon have trodden a
rocky road since then, and on paper they are not the force they were four
years ago. But nobody will underestimate again their capacity to do damage
when everything is at stake.
Cameroon scraped through to the finals, and then looked distinctly
lacklustre under their new coach, Frenchman Henri Michel. Political
wrangling between sports minister Bernard Massoua II and President Biya's
entourage paralysed the national football federation, which at one stage had
two rival chairmen - each with his own ideas. - By May plans to field an
almost entirely new squad gave way to a strategy built around veterans of
1990 - including the 42-year-old Roger Milla. The 1994 squad have been
playing together for nearly two decades. Captain Stephen Tataw leads a
defence that would put fear into the strongest attack. In front, Fran - ois
Omam Biyik scored the Lions' opening goal against Argentina four years ago,
and is relatively unknown only because he has lived so long under Milla's
shadow.
These old Lions could pull one more surprise before retiring for the last
time to their dens.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CMZ  Cameroon, Africa.
</CN>
<XX>
