<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (7): Group A - Fixtures and
facts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Group Fixtures
Saturday, June 18 - US v Switzerland - 11:30 local (15:30 GMT)
Detroit - Pontiac Silverdome
Saturday, June 18
Colombia v Romania - 16:30 local (23:30 GMT)
Los Angeles - Rose Bowl
Wednesday, June 22 - Romania v Switzerland - 16:00 local (20:00 GMT)
Detroit - Pontiac Silverdome
Wednesday, June 22 - US v Colombia - 16:30 local (23:30 GMT)
Los Angeles - Rose Bowl
Sunday, June 26 - US v Romania - 13:00 local (20:00 GMT)
Los Angeles - Rose Bowl
Sunday, June 26 - Switzerland v Colombia - 13:00 local (20:00 GMT)
San Francisco - Stanford Stadium
Star Player: Faustino AsprillaCountry: Colombia
Club: Parma (also: Tulua, Deportivo Cucuta, Nacional Medellin)
Age: 28
Faustino Asprilla is the dangerous soccer genius from central casting. He is
the focus of attention both off and on the field. He is notorious for
crashing fast cars around Parma. In the Cup Winners Cup final he allowed
himself to be distracted by Arsenal's defenders and spent much of the match
involved in arguments with the referee. - He is a devil,' said Franco
Baresi, the Italian defender. Yet Asprilla can also be divine. If he hits
his best form he could lift this talented Colombian team towards the World
Cup on his powerful shoulders.
Key Game: US v Switzerland (June 18 - Detroit)
This group will be decided as much by strength of nerve as depth of talent.
Colombia and Romania both have a habit of failing to fulfil their potential.
Switzerland and US are largely unknown quantities. Both have good players
but both squads contain many players who have largely been sheltered from
top level competition. This match will not only set the tone for this group
but for how the whole World Cup is received by Americans. The host nation
loves a winner and ignores a loser. A US victory could suddenly convince
Americans that soccer is a worthwhile sport and not just a nice hobby for
schoolgirls. -
High-flyer: Ciriaco Sforza, star of Switzerland's midfield
Home grown talent: John Harkes playing for the US is tackled by Paul Ince of
England
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
