<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-2704</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EFQDGAHQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (4): Group A - Romania
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY OLIVER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Only one eastern European club has won the European Cup, Romania's Steaua
Bucharest in 1986, and of that region's three representatives in the World
Cup, Russia, Bulgaria and Romania, the latter is the most likely to make an
impact in America. Romanian footballers are fiery and temperamental but
above all they have a flair and skill that will - make them hard to beat.
Gheorghe Hagi, the Maradona of the Carpathians', is the most skilful
footballer to have come out of the country. He is the creative influence of
the side but has a questionable temperament and can be a destructive
influence on the side.
The 1990 World Cup was a showcase for Romanian footballers in their attempts
to find a way out of the country. Ile Dumitrescu will want to use USA 94 the
same way. He is Steaua's top forward, but the club can no longer hang on to
players of his class.
As the club scene has declined, more attention has been focused on the
national team. Anghel Iordanescu's side has plenty of promise and a strong
backbone of experienced players. In attack, Dumitrescu will be partnered by
Milan's forgotten forward Florin Radiucioiu. In midfield Hagi will be
partnered by his Brescia team mate Ioan Sabau.
The Romanians should have no trouble qualifying from this group and, given
the right draw in the second round, could go further. It all depends on
their attitude. If Hagi is on song it will take a good team to beat them.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ROZ  Romania, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
