<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / FT Guide to World Cup Football (2): The last unconquered
frontier - Whether the Cup leaves most Americans ignorant about football
will depend on television and the success of the home team / A look at the
nation where baseball is king - US Soccer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HAVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Disregard what the cynics of international football say. When the new world
champions of the game are crowned in Los Angeles on July 17, the World Cup
will have been a big success.
While it is true that many Americans know little about professional football
 -or soccer, as they call it - they know plenty about putting on a good
show. The 1994 World Cup will be promoted with typical American flair. The
organisation of the tournament will be smooth, the media facilities
second-to-none. The stadiums will be mostly large and modern, and in some
cases spectacular. Most important of all, the big games will be played
before enthusiastic and peaceful crowds.
Yet, if the developed football world of south America and Europe judges the
tournament a triumph, will it matter if the heart of the undeveloped
football world - the host nation itself - finds the event a less than
overwhelming experience?
Will it matter if, after a month of Brazilians and Bolivians, Irish and
Italians, Colombians and Cameroonians, ordinary Americans shrug their
shoulders and turn their attention to the more familiar rhythms of major
league baseball, of the Dodgers and Giants, Yankees and Red Sox?
The conventional wisdom is that the World Cup will matter a great deal, at
least to the development of the professional game in the US. The Federation
of International Football Associations (Fifa), the sport's governing body,
selected the US as host for 1994 because it believed the World Cup would
spur the establishment of a new professional league in the US, the last
great unconquered territory for the world game'. - Fifa remembers only too
well how the only previous attempt to colonise the US ended, when superstars
like Pele and Beckenbauer failed to prevent the high-flying North American
Soccer League (NASL) from crashing to the ground in 1985, burdened by
financial losses and public indifference. This time, it is putting its faith
in the restorative powers of the World Cup.
Yet, if the tournament is to capture the imagination of Americans, it will
have to be done through television. This will be a difficult task, because
football has a poor reputation as a spectator sport among armchair fans in
the US, who are used to being fed a diet of action-packed, high-scoring
games presented on television in short bursts, regularly punctuated by
commercials. Watching football, however, requires concentration and
patience, and if viewers are to be turned on by the games, they will have to
feature plenty of electrifying plays and spectacular goals. - Unfortunately,
international football has become less exciting in recent years, with
defence-minded teams scoring fewer goals. At the last World Cup, the US
media made great play of the negative team tactics and low scores. The image
presented to the US public then - of a boring, often incom-prehensible game
 -lingers today, and it will require a fundamental change in the approach of
the players and coaches for that image to be reversed.
While it is crucial that the World Cup presents exciting football, Fifa and
the US organisers know that it is almost as important that the home team
performs well, or at least well enough to sustain the domestic public's
interest throughout much of the month-long tournament. As Alan Rothenberg,
head of the US World Cup organising committee, said recently: I don't like
to put pressure on our team, but a lot rides on how the US does.'
Although the host country has progressed through to the second round in
previous World Cups, this summer the US will be one of the weakest of the 24
teams playing, and is in a tough group. For the hosts, surviving the first
round of group games will be a considerable achievement.
Ultimately, the World Cup is not only expected to present a great spectacle,
but also generate enough lasting interest in the game to ensure that
football in the US grows beyond its mainly amateur roots into an important
professional sport. The football authorities, ready to cash-in on the World
Cup, are already planning a new league for 1995.
Yet, those who have been closely involved in US football for many years
contend that the World Cup will not decide the fate of their game. Clive
Toye, head of the New York host committee and a former president of the New
York Cosmos of the old NASL, believes football will grow as a sport in the
US with or without the World Cup.
He says there is no need for the home team to do well, or for the World Cup
to win over fans from basketball or baseball fans. In the long run, it
doesn't matter a damn whether the US team goes out in the first round or
wins the World Cup, because the game is progressing up through the
generations in a very handy way .. Soccer is now the second most popular
game for participants in this country. Those are the fans of the future.'
Football is certainly popular with many Americans of both sexes. Today, an
estimated 15m people play football in the US, more than any team sport
except basketball, and at universities there are more soccer' teams than
American football teams. At the professional level, the country has a
well-established if minor league of 72 teams.
Some observers of the US sports scene, however, are not convinced that a
fully-fledged professional football league will succeed in the US just
because millions of people play the game for fun. John Jeansonne, a
journalist who covers international sports for New York Newsday, says:
Soccer in the US is a tremendous participation sport .. but it's just not
something that Americans tend to follow as spectators. I don't believe the
World Cup will change that, any more than a very successful Los Angeles
Olympics changed our passion for athletics, which continues to disappear
from the landscape of spectator sports in the US.'
Yet, to those like Toye, who have helped nurture the sport in the a over the
years, the millions of Americans who play football represent the roots of
the game, roots which will one day bear fruit. If the World Cup acts as a
temporary fertiliser, so much the better, but Toye says the football
community in the US is not relying on the tournament to determine its
future.
</TEXT>
<XX>
