<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Copper and aluminium lead base
metals back into bull run
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Commodities Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Base metals' bullish bandwagon appeared to be back on course yesterday after
Wednesday's setbacks.
The London Metal Exchange's three months delivery copper price climbed back
above the psychologically significant Dollars 2,400-a-tonne mark while the
aluminium market moved towards its next upside resistance area.
Other LME contracts were also higher, with three months zinc just managing
to regain its toe-hold above Dollars 1,000 a tonne and lead equalling its
recent 20 month high.
'The other metals were looking softer, but when copper and aluminium start
to go higher, people change their views,' one trader told the Reuters news
agency.
Once the three months copper price became re-established above Dollars 2,400
fresh speculative buying emerged to maintain it, and the market's firmness
was underpinned by a narrowing in the discount for cash metal. The
'contango' (as the discount is known in the trade) against three months
metal was reduced from Dollars 18 to Dollars 15.
Aluminium also benefited from a resurgence of speculative buying, which
helped the three months position clear the Dollars 1,440-a-tonne level and
reach a Dollars 38-month high before running into resistance near Dollars
1,450. At the close it stood at Dollars 1,444.50 a tonne, up Dollars 10.75
on the day and Dollars 38.25 on the week so far.
Traders told Reuters that the recent change in sentiment - with voluntary
output cuts generally expected to start wearing down stocks soon - pointed
to upside objectives of about Dollars 1,460 being secured before long.
The tin market continued to match moves in the LME's major metals, with
early losses being negated in the afternoon's general rally. However, there
was not enough enthusiasm behind the buying for prices to break
significantly higher and the three months position closed at Dollars
5,667.50 a tonne, up Dollars 22.50 on the day.
Nickel prices had been pushing higher from the start of trading, with some
fresh buying helping the three months price to break through Dollars 6,400
and reach Dollars 6,500 a tonne at one stage. Chart-based resistance emerged
around that level, however, and the price closed at Dollars 6,482.50 a
tonne. But that still represented a gain of Dollars 39.50.
Traders explained zinc's relatively lacklustre performance - up Dollars 1.50
at Dollars 1,001 a tonne - as a reflection of the heavy stocks burden that
is still overhanging the market.
</TEXT>
