<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / International Bonds: Ontario targets Japanese investors with
Y100bn issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Province of Ontario achieved a minor feat yesterday, in view of current
market conditions, when its Y100bn offering of seven-year bonds put it well
ahead of its funding programme for the current year.
According to joint lead manager Daiwa, Ontario has now raised CDollars 4bn
of its borrowing requirement of CDollars 7.7bn for 1994, although the
province also expects to pre-borrow a further CDollars 2bn to CDollars 3bn
for next year.
The offering was launched during Tokyo's trading day since the bonds were
targeted mainly at Japanese investors, who were attracted by the 4.40 per
cent coupon.
Syndicate managers said that the pricing of the bonds was aggressive when
compared with other euroyen deals.
For example, Italy's seven-year bonds were trading at a yield spread of
around 35 to 40 basis points over Japanese government bonds.
However, they pointed out that Japanese investors looked at coupon levels
rather than yield spreads when they made investment decisions.
When the bonds were freed to trade, the spread was unchanged.
There was talk in the market that most of the orders for Ontario's bonds
went to the joint lead managers - so much so that members of the syndicate
resorted to selling their allocations back to them.
There were also reports that a similar situation had occurred shortly after
the launch of the Kingdom of Belgium's long-awaited Dollars 500m offering of
five-year eurobonds, the other main deal of the day.
The pricing of Belgium's bonds, at 24 basis points over the when-issued
five-year Treasury, was widely regarded as spot on.
When the bonds started to trade, the spread was unchanged despite the
volatility in the underlying Treasury market.
The market is gearing up for Fannie Mae's first global bond offering, which
is scheduled to be launched next Wednesday.
Joint lead managers J. P. Morgan and Merrill Lynch held a conference call
with syndicate members late yesterday afternoon.
The offering is widely expected to raise up to Dollars 1.5bn, have a 10-year
maturity and be priced to yield around 25 basis points over Treasuries.
</TEXT>
