<DATE>940617
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / Government Bonds: Supply fears push European prices to new
lows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bears continued to ravage the market yesterday, pushing government bond
prices in several European markets to new lows for this year in volatile
trading.
The overnight fall in US Treasuries got European bonds off to a weak start.
Moreover, supply fears continue to overhang the markets, where sellers and
issuers continue to outnumber buyers.
'At the moment it is all about supply,' says Mr Kirit Shah, international
bond strategist at First Chicago. 'Supply from bulls who didn't sell earlier
on, supply from governments and now from emerging economies and corporates
into the economic recovery.'
Although he says bonds are in for a correction, he expects supply pressures
to cap the upside. 'We could have a bounce, but don't expect any firework
rallies,' he warned.
UK gilts fell sharply at the open, pressured by weakness in the US. The
short end of the yield curve came under further pressure from Wednesday's
statements by Bank of England governor Mr Eddie George, which were seen to
prepare the ground for a pre-emptive interest-rate increase.
The long end of the yield curve outperformed the short end on hopes that
tight monetary policy would curb future inflation, but weakened on the day.
The 8 3/4 per cent gilt due 2017 fell by  27/32 to 102 1/4 .
This dampened expectations that the Bank of England today will announce an
ultra-long-dated gilt auction, a hope which has buzzed around the market in
recent days.
'Today's sell-off makes it less likely they'll fund at the long end,' said
Mr Ifty Islam, fixed income strategist at Merrill Lynch, who says another
floating-rate issue is possible.
German bunds fell to a new low in the futures market, but recouped most of
the losses in late short-covering to end only slightly lower. However, the
mood remains fragile and dealers expect further volatility.
French bonds fell sharply, causing the 10-year French yield spread over
German bonds to jump to 53 basis points, from 43 basis points on Wednesday.
The Bank of France's latest 10 basis point cut in its intervention rate to
5.2 per cent lent little support, having been widely expected. Meanwhile,
although the Treasury's latest auction of two and five-year notes went
relatively smoothly, much of it was seen to have ended on traders' books.
Southern European markets were again badly hit by budget worries in Italy,
political jitters in Spain and a Portuguese bond auction where the average
yield soared by 125 basis points from the previous auction in late May.
The US Treasury bond market, focusing on a weaker tone in commodities,
rebounded yesterday despite mostly unfavourable economic news.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  1/4 ahead at
86 5/16 , with the yield slipping to 7.365 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note was  1/16 better at 100 1/8 , to yield 5.787 per cent.
With the market reeling from a sharp rise in the price of crude oil and
other commodities the previous afternoon, traders were greeted yesterday
morning by fresh signs of economic acceleration.
The Commerce Department reported that housing starts last month had risen
2.6 per cent, a big surprise for a market expecting a 0.8 per cent decline.
The data suggested the recent tightening of monetary policy has so far
failed to constrain the rate-sensitive construction industry.
The impression of robust growth was reinforced by the weekly report on
initial claims for unemployment benefit, which provides the most up to date
snapshot of the economy's overall health. Yesterday, it showed 11,000 fewer
people had made claims last week than during the previous seven days.
While the two reports were not especially important by themselves, they did
nothing to dispel the sense of confusion reigning in the debt markets.
Recent data, taken as a whole, has not painted a convincing picture, either
favourable or unfavourable, to lead bonds out of their current trading
range.
The same was true of the monthly survey of business conditions issued by the
Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia later in the morning. But the mixed
signals it conveyed were at least enough to trigger a reversal in the
market's decline, especially with analysts looking for even stronger numbers
out of Philadelphia.
By early afternoon, bonds had retraced all of their earlier losses and moved
into positive territory as commodity prices began to drift lower on the
heels of Wednesday's sharp rise.
</TEXT>
