<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / International Company News: Kavner leaves AT&amp;T for CAA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Robert Kavner, head of multimedia products and services at AT&amp;T, has left
the US telecommunications group to join Creative Artists Agency, Hollywood's
top talent agency.
The hiring of Mr Kavner is a significant coup for CAA and a big loss to
AT&amp;T. A former chief financial officer of the telecommunications group, Mr
Kavner was a key figure in the merger of AT&amp;T's computer operations with the
computer group NCR in 1991-1992, and in the recent forging of several
alliances between AT&amp;T and US multimedia companies.
His knowledge of the computer and telecommunications industries is such that
he was on the shortlist last year to replace Mr John Akers as chairman of
IBM.
After being appointed head of AT&amp;T's multimedia products and services
division last summer, 51-year-old Mr Kavner became one of the group's top
four executives. He had responsibility for employing AT&amp;T's
telecommunications and computer expertise to spearhead a push into the
interactive multimedia business.
CAA said that Mr Kavner would 'lead in the identification and development of
opportunities for the agency's clients in the merging digital, interactive
and networked media'.
Mr Kavner's move to CAA is the latest sign of how the efforts of US
companies to exploit the development of the so-called 'information
super-highway' is blurring the lines between the entertainment,
communications and computer technology industries.
It is also evidence of the growing power of CAA, which, under the leadership
of chairman Mr Michael Ovitz, has been building a presence in other fields
related to the entertainment business.
</TEXT>
