<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / International Company News: CS chief dampens fear over
Creditanstalt bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC FREY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Rainer Gut, the chairman of CS Holdings, yesterday said Creditanstalt
would remain 'a proud and independent Austrian bank with its own identity'
if CS succeeded in winning control of the bank.
Mr Gut said he was well aware of political opposition to the efforts of the
Swiss banking group to take control of Creditanstalt, Austria's banking
flagship. He felt CS had an even chance of winning control against
competition from a rival Austrian-led consortium.
Mr Gut said he would prefer to buy all the government's 49 per cent stake
but would be content with a smaller stake in the short term. He declined to
disclose his offer price.
Based on Creditanstalt's share price, the government stake is worth about
Sch14bn (Dollars 1.2bn). Mr Ferdinand Lacina, the Austrian finance minister,
has said his decision would not be based on price but on national interest
and the interests of Creditanstalt.
Mr Gut was in Vienna to meet Mr Lacina, who wants to privatise Creditanstalt
quickly and encourage public support for his offer.
His earlier announcement that CS was aiming for a 100 per cent control of
Creditanstalt has aroused controversy in Austria. This led to the formation
of the rival bid.
