<HEADLINE>
FT  17 JUN 94 / UK Company News: Materials handling boosts FKI - Hardware
side moves into Europe with Pounds 25.8m castors purchase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FKI, the electrical engineering and electronic components group, yesterday
announced a 38 per cent rise in profits and the acquisition of Rhombus, a
German castor manufacturer, for Pounds 25.8m.
Pre-tax profits increased from Pounds 38m to Pounds 52.3m. Turnover advanced
5 per cent, from Pounds 756.1m to Pounds 794.5m, including a contribution of
Pounds 46.8m from acquisitions. Mr Bob Beeston, chief executive, said the
group had done everything it had set out to do during the year, raising
margins on steady turnover.
Nevertheless, the share price closed 9 1/2 p down at 163 1/2 p.
Rhombus is being acquired from Albert Schulte Sohne for Pounds 5.4m cash and
the assumption of Pounds 20.4m of debt. Mr Beeston said it would take FKI's
hardware division into Europe for the first time, complementing Faultless
Caster which is the market leader in North America with a 21 per cent share.
The German company has 15 per cent of the European market, with a modern
factory in Wermelskirchen and another in Malaysia. Customers include makers
of shopping trolleys, hospital beds, and home and office furniture.
It is not expected to make a contribution to FKI's profits until next year.
FKI operates through five divisions - hardware, materials handling,
automotive, engineering and process control. Profits increased in all five,
with materials handling the outstanding performer. Profits in the division
rose from Pounds 8.5m to Pounds 17.5m on turnover of Pounds 176.9m (Pounds
173.3m).
Both the materials handling and the automotive divisions benefited from the
improvement in the US automotive sector. The automotive division lifted
profits from Pounds 2.4m to Pounds 4.6m on turnover of Pounds 171.7m (Pounds
152.4m).
The hardware division made profits of Pounds 20.3m (Pounds 16.1m) on sales
of Pounds 172.1m (Pounds 132.6m), helped by the Pounds 66.5m acquisition of
Truth, the US manufacturer of hinges, operating and locking mechanisms for
windows and doors, last November.
Engineering profits edged ahead to Pounds 10.7m (Pounds 10.5m) on turnover
of Pounds 97.6m (Pounds 100.8m), while process control profits were Pounds
7.3m (Pounds 5.2m) on sales of Pounds 176.2m (Pounds 161.4m).
Mr Eric Bowers, finance director, said that margins had improved from 5.9
per cent to 7.6 per cent, with margins of 8.7 per cent in the second half.
Gearing was 50 per cent at the end of the year, but would reach 60 per cent
with the acquisition of Rhombus.
Earnings per share rose from 6.2p to 8.22p. A final dividend of 2.2p is
proposed, giving a total for the year of 3.7p (3p).
COMMENT
The constant emphasis on margins and the reluctance to push for revenue
growth at any price has certainly paid dividends. It has to be asked whether
the rate of growth can be maintained. However, this year Truth should kick
in strongly, and the following year the latest acquisition will be adding to
the bottom line. Pre-tax profits of Pounds 68m this year give a prospective
multiple of 16. It looks as though high expectations of the current
management have been fully reflected in the share price, and yesterday saw
some profit taking.
</TEXT>
